@node Overview

I wanted to grab a nice pointer...

When playing around with some new software for the Amiga I found out
that one of them used a pretty nice mouse pointer to indicate some graphical
operation. I wanted that pointer for my own code. Enter Iconizer! No,
Iconizer couldn't do it. Enter ADPro! No, ADPro couldn't do it either.
I found out that these programs are only capable of grabbing "old" pointers
from old programs.

GrabPointer is capable of grabbing new "pointerclass" pointers from new
OS3.0 conforming software. It will generate C source code on success.

This is a program for programmers.

@endnode

@node Using

What it does...

Since OS3.0 (v39) some programs use a new scheme allowing hi-res pointers
for instance. This is possible through the BOOPSI system.
These programs create an instance of a "pointerclass" object by calling
NewObjectA() and later call SetWindowPointerA() to display it.

GrabPointer installs itself into NewObjectA() and will examine all calls with
"pointerclass" as argument. GrabPointer will then generate the C source that
could have made this call. See @{"here" LINK examplegrab.c/main} for an example.
The resulting code is sent to stdout (which normally equals the console window
unless you redirect the output).

That's all there is to it.


How to use it...

1. Start GrabPointer from Shell. The patch will then be installed.
   Make sure you redirect the output if you want to save the result.
   (e.g. GrabPointer >grabfile.c)

2. Start the program you want to grab a mouse pointer from.
   Produce the pointer you are looking for by using the program.

3. Quit GrabPointer and remove the patch by pressing CTRL-C.

4. Examine the file. The result was either generated when the software
   was started or when the pointer was produced. If the first case is true,
   then the output might contain code for many pointers. (It is up to the
   software to decide when to call NewObjectA().) If there is no output from
   GrabPointer, try another program. The software is probably using the old
   scheme then.

@endnode

@node Legal

FREEWARE
GrabPointer1.0 is FreeWare, enjoy.

You have the right to use the code and source as you please.
However, the author (that's me) would like that you give him credit for this
marvelous piece of code if you decide to enhance it.

DISCLAIMER
The author is not responsible for any loss of data, damages to
software or hardware that may result directly or indirectly from
the use of this program.

LEGAL NOTICE
I really don't think there are any lawsuit hungry companies out there that
will be upset if someone grab their mouse pointers and use it in their
own code. But just to be on the safe side, GrabPointer is limited to grab no
more than 16 pixel wide pointers. Calling a 16 pixel wide object an artwork
must be asking too much. This program is made to bring a standard look to
Amiga mouse pointers and simplify the work for programmers.
Finally, the use or misuse of this program is of course your responsibility.

@endnode

